Throughout the inland state of Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century is still strong, and so is the longing to sail the Pacific again.
Hopes may be at their highest in decades, while Bolivia awaits a verdict from the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of voting.
"Bolivia has momentum, a sense of community and clarity, and of course awaits with a positive look at the outcome," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the decision of the International Court of Justice on big screens across the country and hope that the court in The Hague will agree with Bolivia that Chile, after decades of discussions, is obliged to negotiate to grant Bolivia sovereignty over an area with access to the sea.
