"We are about to return to the Pacific Ocean," he promised at the end of August.
But analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will take Bolivia’s side – and that there would be no major changes if it did.
The United Nations Assembly, based in the Netherlands, has no power to override Chilean territory and has stipulated that it cannot determine the outcome of possible discussions.
The fact that the International Court of Justice pronounces its verdict just six months after the final arguments were heard indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And instead of advancing the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have been a setback.
"The case of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian leadership," Zárate said.
Morales's belligerent rhetoric has eliminated the remaining Chilean benevolence, she said.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the discussions at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
