John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic achievements behind them, and it continues in 2018 with yet another number of outstanding exam results, which are reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other endeavors in the local community.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to their students and parents.
The independent schools try to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can compile and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we experience that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it strikes the heart.”
It’s an important reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can look at the latest exam results this year, that language is the highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by SCIS’ 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as subject selection at the same level as STEM topics (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools of thought and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17% of the reasons employers were unable to fill vacancies were related to lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more important in terms of preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career young people choose, if they have learned a different language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a lead to competitors.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language education for those who are children today.
Speaking multiple languages, especially languages from developing countries, gives children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, there is a difference between schools in which languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a number of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to delivering a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed no matter what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be really important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this award to Scotland’s youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
