While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps. But his speech seemed important as it did not unequivocally reject unilateral disarmament, as has been the case otherwise previously from Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim vowed to work "nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula" while Trump vowed to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has demanded a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown opposition to softening tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first' and expands the pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose by force and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream come true among people who don’t know who we are.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions reinforce our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a summit between Kim and Trump, as the U.S. leader highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If nuclear disarmament were to be negotiated with South Korea and not the United States, the negotiations would not be so locked in.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that firing North Korea’s missiles at the US mainland was inevitable, after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
Last year, Trump at the UN threatened to “total destruction” of North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for showing courage in terms of disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions had to remain until North Korea pulled down.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timetable for these actions, but said "it doesn't matter whether it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
