What is the Global Citizens Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York City hosts the Global Citizens Festival – an annual music festival with a very impressive range of artists and an equally impressive goal; to end the world’s poverty.
For the seventh time, the Global Citizens Festival will welcome tens of thousands of people on Central Park’s large lawn, where they can look forward to concerts with Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes. At the same time, the festival will raise awareness about the real goal of ending extreme poverty by 2030.
Started in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international interest organization that fights to end poverty by increasing the number of active opponents.
To receive a free ticket to the event (if you do not want to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers must perform a number of tasks or "actions". For example, doing volunteer work, writing to a world leader, making a phone call or other meaningful action that can raise awareness about the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been now that they have 12 years left to reach the goal?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really change, or is it just another case of so-called “clictivism” – that is, that people feel that they are making a difference by signing a signature collection online or making a Twitter post?
Since 2011, Global Citizen has recorded more than 19 million “acts” from its members targeting various targets.
They believe that these actions have encouraged world leaders to make binding goals and policy actions equivalent to more than $37 billion, which by 2030 is expected to have affected more than 2.25 billion people.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 goals and actions that had become due to their actions, amounting to over $10 billion that had already been paid or collected.
The group estimates that these funds have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide so far.
One of the main goals is The Power of Nutrition, which is a collaboration between investors and actionable individuals. They aim to “help children reach their full potential” and promise $35 million to address nutritional problems in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the help of the English government, donors, governments of other countries and world citizens like you, social injustice with malnutrition can become a footnote in the history books,” The Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracey Ullman told audiences at a London concert in April 2018.
The group also said that the UK government has now pledged funds to improve nutrition for mothers and children after receiving more than 5,000 calls online. This project, Power of Nutrition, will help five million mothers and children with nutritional advice.
In response to one of the website’s frequently asked questions, “What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen wrote: "It will be a long and hard fight, and sometimes we will stumble and make mistakes.
But as with the civil rights movement and the movements against apartheid, it will succeed because we are stronger together.”
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are among the performers at this year’s festival in New York. Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman will be hosts.
