He said: “To this day, the feelings of being worth remembering and feeling different have been the things that have given me the strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove that he was “something,” he said, so he didn’t disappoint everyone when they learned about his sexuality.
The double Olympic bronze winner has become a high-profile LGBT advocate and used his participation at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal for a decriminalization of homosexuality in several countries.
He said he spoke out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without negative consequences, and he would give others “hope.”
The three-time world champion said he was “surprised” when he fell in love with a man – American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013.
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference had never been a problem.
He said it’s hard to find someone of the same age who has experienced similar ups and downs when going through so much at such a young age – he went to his first Olympics at the age of 14, and his father died of cancer three years later.
The couple became parents in June to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said "his whole perspective" had changed.
“If you had asked me last year, it would all be about me winning a gold medal,” he said.
"But there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son has the same name as his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept him to die, and one of the last things he asked was if they had gotten tickets to London in 2012 – as he would sit in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him he wouldn't be there at that time.
I held his hand when his breathing stopped, and it first became clear to me that he was not immortal when he stopped breathing and was dead.”
The following year, Daley took part in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
“I just knew that’s what I had dreamed of all my life – diving in front of a home audience at the Olympics. There was nothing that could beat that feeling,” he said.
It was also the inspiration for his first choice of song – Proud by Heather Small – which had meant a lot during the run-up to the Olympics and still gave him goose skin.
