Germany's new warship postponed again
The newest frigate of the German Navy should have been ready in 2014 to replace warships from the Cold War. But the Germans must wait at least another year due to technical problems and an escalating price, local media write.
The deployment of the largest ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg frigate class, "Rheinland-Pfalz", has been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a spokesman from the military.
The ship should have become part of the fleet in 2014, but post-delivery problems have plagued the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class ordered back in 2007 will replace the aging frigates of the Bremen class.
They are known to have a powerful cannon, a wide range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as stealth technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature of the newest frigates is a minor maintenance need: it should be possible to keep the frigates away from home ports for up to two years.
But the repeated delays mean that the advanced warships – which are said to make Germany appear as an overseas power factor – will already be obsolete when they are deployed.
The failed F125 frigate created headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had delivered a ship back to the shipbuilder after delivery.
Not much was known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware failures" that rendered the warship useless in combat situations.
Software failure was of particular importance, as the ships from the Baden-Wuerttemberg class must be controlled by a crew of 120 sailors – that’s only half of that crew from the older Bremen frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was too heavy, reducing its performance and limiting the fleet's ability for future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne Rhineland-Palatinate is said to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the cost of the project, which includes training of the crew, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), with an initial price of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming even more important in the light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval force is shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German government's defence committee, admitted earlier this year that the fleet "runs dry for deployment-ready ships."
The official said that the problem has grown over time because the old ships were taken out of service without being replaced.
He complained that none of the frigates from the Baden-Wuerttemberg class were ready to join the fleet.
The National Trust listens to the secret lives of bats
New research from an area in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape when they hunt.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the unique behaviour of flying mammals and will help in the work on future conservation efforts.
The study is conducted by scientists from the Scottish National Trust and follows common bats, dwarf bats, elongated bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed in carefully selected locations in the area to record the bat activities throughout the season.
Data is also collected by NTS staff and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analyses of the sound recordings will reveal the frequencies of the fleas and show which species does what.
To produce a detailed landscape picture of their behavior, a report and a map of the habitat are made.
NTS Conservation Advisor Rob Dewar hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help to determine the benefits of habitat conservation interventions such as the creation of meadows and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and the UK has fallen dramatically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban expansion projects that affect shipowners and restrict their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly traps, chemical treatment of building materials and attacks from pets.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because they hunt primarily at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to find insects and fly away from obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the preservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect shipyards and sometimes do rescue operations.
The organization has even made Scotland’s first and only dedicated tiger reserve at the Threave area in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland’s tiger species.
The caretaker of the area, David Thompson, says it is an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a really good area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the good habitat.
There’s a lot you don’t know about bats, so working here and elsewhere can help you understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed the importance of looking for bats before doing maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest could kill up to 400 females and young, thereby risking the destruction of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how populations evolve."
